## 🚩 Findings

### 🚩 Flag 1: Initial Sign-in Failure Review

#### Objective  
Confirm the identity involved in the suspicious activity by matching the targeted user against known failed sign in attempts.

#### Flag Value  
m.smith@lognpacific.org / Mark Smith

#### What to Hunt  
Failed sign in attempts tied to the suspected user, including the principal name, identity, IP address, authentication method, and protocol used during the failed attempts.

#### Detection Strategy  
Filter SigninLogs for usernames containing smith and restrict to failed results to identify the targeted account associated with the suspicious authentication activity.

#### KQL Query
```kql
SigninLogs
| where UserPrincipalName contains "smith"
| where ResultSignature == "FAILURE"
| project TimeGenerated, UserPrincipalName, UserId, AuthenticationMethodsUsed, IPAddress,
Identity, AuthenticationProtocol, ResultSignature
```

#### Evidence

#### Why This Matters  
This confirms the victim identity at the start of the hunt and anchors later authentication, inbox rule, and email activity to the correct compromised user account.

---

### 🚩 Flag 2: Initial Successful Access Source Identification

#### Objective  
Determine where the first successful malicious access came from by identifying the IP address and location associated with the successful sign in.

#### Flag Value  
205.147.16.190, Netherlands, later activity from Great Britain

#### What to Hunt  
Successful sign in events for the compromised account, with emphasis on remote IP address, geolocation, and the time the first successful session was established.

#### Detection Strategy  
Query SigninLogs for successful authentication events tied specifically to m.smith@lognpacific.org and review the IP and location fields to isolate the attacker’s access point.

#### KQL Query
```kql
SigninLogs
| where UserPrincipalName == "m.smith@lognpacific.org"
| where ResultSignature == "SUCCESS"
| project TimeGenerated, UserPrincipalName, UserId, IPAddress, Identity, ResultSignature,
Location
```

#### Evidence

#### Why This Matters  
This establishes the attacker’s initial access point and provides a pivot value for linking subsequent cloud activity, inbox rule creation, and email abuse to the same session.

